One of the reduction steps in the theory plugin (for strings) I'm working on involves creating a fresh string variable and then asserting some facts about it. I couldn't find any other theory plugins that need to do something like this, so I guessed that the best approach would be to simulate what `smt2parser` does when it encounters a `(declare-const)` expression. To this end I have the following code:

```
app * theory_str::mk_str_var(std::string name) {
	context & ctx = get_context();
	ast_manager & m = get_manager();

	sort * string_sort = m.mk_sort(m_strutil.get_family_id(), STRING_SORT);
	char * new_buffer = alloc_svect(char, name.length() + 1);
	strcpy(new_buffer, name.c_str());
	symbol sym(new_buffer);

	app * a = m.mk_const(m.mk_const_decl(sym, string_sort));

	ctx.internalize(a, false);
	SASSERT(ctx.get_enode(a) != NULL);
	SASSERT(ctx.e_internalized(a));
	m_basicstr_axiom_todo.push_back(ctx.get_enode(a));

        // some internal stuff I have to keep track of
	variable_set.insert(a);
	internal_variable_set.insert(a);
	track_variable_scope(a);

	return a;
}
```

It seems that this method works sometimes and fails other times. In particular, in one test case I'm working with, I create a temporary variable and make some assertions with it, then the solver pops the context (deallocating that variable in the process), and then later I create a second temporary variable (with a different name). The first variable successfully has the assertions applied; the second one fails the assertion `get_id() >= c_first_decl_id` in `ast/ast.h:547`. This is very strange, and inspecting the object in the debugger seems to suggest that some of its fields don't point to valid memory.

It's definitely not the case that the fresh variable goes out of context before I try to use it. The context doesn't push or pop before this assertion failure; the variable is created and then immediately used in the same method without returning control to the solver.

If it matters, I'm doing all of this inside `final_check_eh()`.

The other strange factor is that code similar to this worked in a previous version of this string solver (Z3str2, built against Z3 4.1.1) with the code:

```
